WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.040 --> 00:00:03.970
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington DC.

00:00:22.590 --> 00:00:26.700 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Annette McLean: Good evening,
welcome to our Founders Day Weekend.

00:00:26.700 --> 00:00:28.840
I'm Anne McLean from the
Library's Concert Office

00:00:28.840 --> 00:00:32.300
and we are very excited
to be celebrating 90 years

00:00:32.300 --> 00:00:35.540
of legendary concerts here at the
Library of Congress this season.

00:00:35.540 --> 00:00:39.850
Nine decades after the
Library opened in October 1925,

00:00:39.850 --> 00:00:41.150
concerts from the Library

00:00:41.150 --> 00:00:43.820
of Congress is alive,
vibrant and colorful.

00:00:43.820 --> 00:00:47.480
And it's exciting and exhilarating
to be celebrating our history

00:00:47.480 --> 00:00:49.320
and looking forward to the future

00:00:49.320 --> 00:00:53.070
with a splendid lineup
of more than 95 events.

00:00:53.070 --> 00:00:56.670
This weekend we're honoring the
150th anniversary of the founder

00:00:56.670 --> 00:01:00.230
of our concerts, Elizabeth Sprague
Coolidge, an extraordinary woman,

00:01:00.230 --> 00:01:04.740
extraordinary philanthropist,
and extraordinary role model.

00:01:04.740 --> 00:01:07.380
Today, October 30th,
is her birthday,

00:01:07.380 --> 00:01:10.450
day that we mark each season
with a special project.

00:01:10.450 --> 00:01:13.540
And I'm happy to say that two of
her great granddaughters are here

00:01:13.540 --> 00:01:17.510
with us, Jose and Peg
[inaudible], so welcome to them.

00:01:17.510 --> 00:01:23.930
[ Applause ]

00:01:23.930 --> 00:01:26.970
Mrs. Coolidge, as many of you
know already, was a brilliant

00:01:26.970 --> 00:01:29.530
and formidable woman,
pianist, composer, [inaudible]

00:01:29.530 --> 00:01:33.020
and a passionate advocate
for chamber music.

00:01:33.020 --> 00:01:37.570
She endowed our superb concert hall
and supervised it's construction.

00:01:37.570 --> 00:01:40.300
She established our concert
series here through a concept

00:01:40.300 --> 00:01:43.550
that was visionary and
radical for its time,

00:01:43.550 --> 00:01:47.810
a public/private partnership, a
path breaking innovation signed

00:01:47.810 --> 00:01:50.370
into law by Calvin Coolidge.

00:01:50.370 --> 00:01:53.880
And if you have our brochure
you can see a reprint image

00:01:53.880 --> 00:01:56.140
of that first bill.

00:01:56.140 --> 00:01:57.530
This was a first.

00:01:57.530 --> 00:02:00.140
Her gesture was a first.

00:02:00.140 --> 00:02:01.560
Her vision and her leadership

00:02:01.560 --> 00:02:04.600
which has made possible
nearly 3000 concerts and more

00:02:04.600 --> 00:02:07.420
than 100 significant
Coolidge Foundation commission

00:02:07.420 --> 00:02:11.720
for the Library was the spark for
our panel tonight, A Leading Role:

00:02:11.720 --> 00:02:14.940
A Conversation on Women
in the Music World.

00:02:14.940 --> 00:02:18.810
And I wanted to say, too, that
you can see in a handsome exhibit

00:02:18.810 --> 00:02:21.280
about Mrs. Coolidge
and her life and career

00:02:21.280 --> 00:02:24.250
over in the James Madison
Building across the street.

00:02:24.250 --> 00:02:27.580
It's beautifully put together and
curated by our two colleagues,

00:02:27.580 --> 00:02:30.930
Robin Rousch [assumed
spelling] and Katelyn Miller.

00:02:30.930 --> 00:02:34.730
This weekend we have concerts that
reflect Mrs. Coolidge's interests

00:02:34.730 --> 00:02:38.140
in music, both very new,
tomorrow's concert --

00:02:38.140 --> 00:02:41.380
or tonight's concert
by a modern master

00:02:41.380 --> 00:02:43.890
and vocal magician, Meredith Monk.

00:02:43.890 --> 00:02:46.140
And also music that was very old.

00:02:46.140 --> 00:02:48.170
Tomorrow we have Pomerium,

00:02:48.170 --> 00:02:52.690
a vocal ensemble performing
music of renaissance masters.

00:02:52.690 --> 00:02:55.780
So I'd like to introduce our
distinguished panel tonight,

00:02:55.780 --> 00:02:59.900
and I'm very grateful
to these speakers.

00:02:59.900 --> 00:03:03.150
We are honored to have as our
featured speaker, Jane Chu,

00:03:03.150 --> 00:03:05.380
Chairman of the National
Endowment of the Arts.

00:03:05.380 --> 00:03:07.510
It's [inaudible] to have you here.

00:03:07.510 --> 00:03:11.700
[ Applause ]

00:03:11.700 --> 00:03:14.730
Chairman Chu is the 11th
chairman of the NEA appointed

00:03:14.730 --> 00:03:17.840
by President Obama in 2014.

00:03:17.840 --> 00:03:21.330
In addition to awarding
nearly $220 million

00:03:21.330 --> 00:03:25.480
in grants during her tenure just to
date, she's also launched a number

00:03:25.480 --> 00:03:29.650
of new programs, and including
one called Creative Connections,

00:03:29.650 --> 00:03:32.450
we'll hear about --
Creativity Connects, pardon me,

00:03:32.450 --> 00:03:33.980
which we'll hear about later.

00:03:33.980 --> 00:03:36.800
She is a pianist and a
former concert presenter,

00:03:36.800 --> 00:03:39.810
and this was of great interest
to us when she was appointed.

00:03:39.810 --> 00:03:45.230
From 2006 to 2014 she was president
and CEO of the Kauffman Center

00:03:45.230 --> 00:03:47.930
for the Performing Arts
in Kansas City, Missouri,

00:03:47.930 --> 00:03:52.980
overseeing a $413 million
campaign to build that center.

00:03:52.980 --> 00:03:55.540
She holds a doctorate
in Philanthropic Studies

00:03:55.540 --> 00:03:57.200
and a background in fundraising

00:03:57.200 --> 00:04:01.720
and development is an
important part of her portfolio.

00:04:01.720 --> 00:04:05.940
We are very, very pleased to be
able to work closely with the NEA

00:04:05.940 --> 00:04:09.130
and we will talk a little bit
more about the intersection

00:04:09.130 --> 00:04:13.760
between public and private funding
and developing those initiates.

00:04:13.760 --> 00:04:17.420
Cellist and educator, Astrid
Schween, is admired internationally

00:04:17.420 --> 00:04:20.580
as both a solo and chamber
artist, long-time member

00:04:20.580 --> 00:04:23.570
of the Lark Quartet, with whom she
has performed here at the Library.

00:04:23.570 --> 00:04:26.960 position:56%
She's now performing with the Boston
Trio and she's a professor of Cello

00:04:26.960 --> 00:04:28.790
at the University of Massachusetts.

00:04:28.790 --> 00:04:32.730
In 2016 she will join the Julliard
String Quartet, whom I know many

00:04:32.730 --> 00:04:36.620
of you are fans of, replacing
cellist Joel Krosnick,

00:04:36.620 --> 00:04:40.520
and will join the faculty
at the Juilliard School.

00:04:40.520 --> 00:04:42.320
Margaret Lioi --

00:04:42.320 --> 00:04:47.040
[ Applause ]

00:04:47.040 --> 00:04:50.670
Margaret Lioi is CEO of Chamber
Music America, founded 28 years ago

00:04:50.670 --> 00:04:53.640
to develop, support and
strengthen the chamber music field,

00:04:53.640 --> 00:04:55.670
and I'm glad to say that the
Library has been a member

00:04:55.670 --> 00:04:59.880
since the very early days of the
founding of the organization.

00:04:59.880 --> 00:05:02.010
She too has a background
very impressive

00:05:02.010 --> 00:05:04.210
in performance and business skills.

00:05:04.210 --> 00:05:06.490
She has an MBA in Arts
Administration,

00:05:06.490 --> 00:05:08.700
and has held the post of
Director or Development

00:05:08.700 --> 00:05:12.400
for the Spoleto Festival USA,
and the Executive Director

00:05:12.400 --> 00:05:16.920
of the Eleanor Naylor
Dana Charitable Trust.

00:05:16.920 --> 00:05:20.090
And I'd like to say that CMA is
a very important commissioner

00:05:20.090 --> 00:05:24.540
of new music, offering a number
of commissions, and we will talk

00:05:24.540 --> 00:05:26.370
about commissioning a little later.

00:05:26.370 --> 00:05:30.590
We would like to get started with
hearing from these experts on many,

00:05:30.590 --> 00:05:36.310
many areas of the world of music
and business as they intersect.

00:05:36.310 --> 00:05:38.830
And we would like to start
off with Astrid Schween.

00:05:38.830 --> 00:05:40.130
&gt;&gt; Astrid Schween: Okay.

00:05:40.130 --> 00:05:41.430
Good evening.

00:05:41.430 --> 00:05:42.730
Hi, this is [inaudible].

00:05:42.730 --> 00:05:47.130
Okay. So I put together a little
narrative of what my life is

00:05:47.130 --> 00:05:50.850
like as a teacher, as a
performer, as a mentor.

00:05:50.850 --> 00:05:53.970
I found this a wonderful
exercise and a great way to kind

00:05:53.970 --> 00:05:59.280
of explore the impact I am and
perhaps am not having on people

00:05:59.280 --> 00:06:03.980
around me, so I've
prepared a little something.

00:06:03.980 --> 00:06:07.630
My perspective on women in the
music world has been shaped

00:06:07.630 --> 00:06:11.060
by my activities as a
performer, teacher and mentor.

00:06:11.060 --> 00:06:15.550
In these roles I've spent much
of my time focusing on aspects

00:06:15.550 --> 00:06:18.730
that are largely technical,
analytical,

00:06:18.730 --> 00:06:20.640
diagnostic and practical.

00:06:20.640 --> 00:06:25.140
As a teacher one of my
primary responsibilities is

00:06:25.140 --> 00:06:27.480
to address the needs
of each student,

00:06:27.480 --> 00:06:31.620 position:56%
and help balance their strengths and
weaknesses as developing cellists.

00:06:31.620 --> 00:06:34.330
Each student is different,
and the work tends to focus

00:06:34.330 --> 00:06:36.840
on individual issues
that are independent

00:06:36.840 --> 00:06:39.920
of race, gender or even age.

00:06:39.920 --> 00:06:42.440
My perspective has
also been influenced

00:06:42.440 --> 00:06:47.120
by a very diverse family life that
included a rich network of friends

00:06:47.120 --> 00:06:50.970
and family members from multiple
cultures and backgrounds.

00:06:50.970 --> 00:06:53.690
My parents even chose my schools

00:06:53.690 --> 00:06:57.320
to reflect a similarly
mixed population.

00:06:57.320 --> 00:07:00.140
There was also never
any doubt at home

00:07:00.140 --> 00:07:03.120
that I would pursue a
professional career.

00:07:03.120 --> 00:07:05.690
And it's nice to see a clip
like that from [inaudible],

00:07:05.690 --> 00:07:08.460
I can understand that motivation.

00:07:08.460 --> 00:07:11.670
I later discovered that these
values, which I took for granted,

00:07:11.670 --> 00:07:15.360
were not necessarily consistent
with some of the conventions

00:07:15.360 --> 00:07:19.500
of the times, such as those
I found during summer visits

00:07:19.500 --> 00:07:22.620
to my father's family
in post war Germany,

00:07:22.620 --> 00:07:27.090 position:56%
or even in some suburban communities
closer to home, or the attitudes

00:07:27.090 --> 00:07:30.920
of some teachers that boys,
as future breadwinners,

00:07:30.920 --> 00:07:35.200
would be more focused
attention than girls.

00:07:35.200 --> 00:07:38.480
My most direct mentorship
experience as a young cellist was

00:07:38.480 --> 00:07:41.850
with the great cellist,
Jacqueline du Pre.

00:07:41.850 --> 00:07:45.900
Through a series of lucky events
I was able to work with her

00:07:45.900 --> 00:07:49.190
and made numerous trips to London
over the course of seven years,

00:07:49.190 --> 00:07:51.380
while still a student at Juilliard.

00:07:51.380 --> 00:07:53.920
My lessons with Jacqueline
were unique.

00:07:53.920 --> 00:07:57.670
As someone who had lost the ability
to play because of her illness,

00:07:57.670 --> 00:08:01.130
she learned to communicate
the essentials by singing

00:08:01.130 --> 00:08:04.400
and making gestures with her arms.

00:08:04.400 --> 00:08:05.940
We listened to recordings

00:08:05.940 --> 00:08:09.430
and she would explain what she
had been thinking interpretively

00:08:09.430 --> 00:08:11.310
and while on stage.

00:08:11.310 --> 00:08:15.880
These musically in-depth sessions
always included at least one meal,

00:08:15.880 --> 00:08:18.360
several cups of tea,
and lots of stories

00:08:18.360 --> 00:08:21.650
about her life as a touring artist.

00:08:21.650 --> 00:08:25.870
Normally you spend one hour
with your teacher each week,

00:08:25.870 --> 00:08:31.010 position:56%
or a little more with studio class
time, but in this case I was invited

00:08:31.010 --> 00:08:33.390
into the thought process
and creative process

00:08:33.390 --> 00:08:35.740
in a way that was completely new.

00:08:35.740 --> 00:08:39.340
Jacqueline took the time to share
with me and explain from the point

00:08:39.340 --> 00:08:41.960
of view of a performer
the nuts and bolts

00:08:41.960 --> 00:08:44.210
of assembling an interpretation

00:08:44.210 --> 00:08:47.370
and rending it practically
through the instrument.

00:08:47.370 --> 00:08:51.030
To me this was the
essence of mentorship.

00:08:51.030 --> 00:08:55.530
Women in the music world, with
quotes, took on new meaning

00:08:55.530 --> 00:08:59.870
when I became of an all
women string quartet.

00:08:59.870 --> 00:09:02.640
I started traveling
extensively with the Lark Quartet

00:09:02.640 --> 00:09:05.150
for concerts, tours
and competitions.

00:09:05.150 --> 00:09:09.030
This very valuable professional
experience included both mentoring

00:09:09.030 --> 00:09:13.380
students of my own during quartet
residencies at various institutions

00:09:13.380 --> 00:09:16.460
around the country, as well
as being mentored by some

00:09:16.460 --> 00:09:19.460
of the great chamber music
artists of the generation,

00:09:19.460 --> 00:09:23.230
who worked with us as we
prepared for competitions.

00:09:23.230 --> 00:09:29.210
These included members of the
Budapest, Amadeus, Bardeen,

00:09:29.210 --> 00:09:31.990
[inaudible] Juilliard
and LaSalle quartets.

00:09:31.990 --> 00:09:34.380
With Jackie my lessons were all

00:09:34.380 --> 00:09:37.110
about how do you make
this particular sound,

00:09:37.110 --> 00:09:41.580
how do you sustain this line,
how do you play with more power,

00:09:41.580 --> 00:09:47.060 position:56%
how do you conserve your energy, how
does one imitate the human voice.

00:09:47.060 --> 00:09:50.460 position:56%
With these quartet masters it
tended to be more about illustrating

00:09:50.460 --> 00:09:55.400
to the audience the architecture
and form of a complete work.

00:09:55.400 --> 00:09:58.850
From these people I learned
a lot about collaboration,

00:09:58.850 --> 00:10:01.230
how to assemble a piece
and convey it's substance

00:10:01.230 --> 00:10:03.560 position:56%
to an audience, and how to rehearse.

00:10:03.560 --> 00:10:06.110
It was also essential to
my development as a coach

00:10:06.110 --> 00:10:08.600
of other chamber musicians.

00:10:08.600 --> 00:10:11.690
My time with the Lark Quartet
also brought experience

00:10:11.690 --> 00:10:15.790
with commissioning composers and
premiering and recording new works.

00:10:15.790 --> 00:10:19.510
The Lark was founded on the
mission to expand the repertoire

00:10:19.510 --> 00:10:21.350
through funded commissions.

00:10:21.350 --> 00:10:24.440
During these years we worked a
great deal with organizations

00:10:24.440 --> 00:10:29.600
like Chamber Music America, thank
you, applying for both residency

00:10:29.600 --> 00:10:31.290
and commissioning grants.

00:10:31.290 --> 00:10:32.820
We worked with other organizations

00:10:32.820 --> 00:10:35.400
such as the Minnesota's
Composers Forum,

00:10:35.400 --> 00:10:38.000
the National Orchestral
Association, which was funded

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:40.790
by the Judson Foundation,
and the Mars

00:10:40.790 --> 00:10:43.960
and Alma Shapiro Fund,
to name a few.

00:10:43.960 --> 00:10:47.150
Interestingly, all of these
organizations featured women

00:10:47.150 --> 00:10:49.100
in leadership roles.

00:10:49.100 --> 00:10:52.660
And it was with each of them
that we had direct communication

00:10:52.660 --> 00:10:55.860
when making our applications
for funds.

00:10:55.860 --> 00:10:58.840
Over the years the Quartet
commissioned numerous works

00:10:58.840 --> 00:11:01.580
from some of the most
celebrated composers.

00:11:01.580 --> 00:11:05.090
These pieces were significant
for our career building.

00:11:05.090 --> 00:11:08.910
Being the first ensemble to record
them helped establish the Quartet

00:11:08.910 --> 00:11:13.790
in the mainstream of the American
chamber music scene for many years.

00:11:13.790 --> 00:11:15.380
Some of the commissions
included works

00:11:15.380 --> 00:11:18.520
for string quartet plus a guest
artist, which opened the way

00:11:18.520 --> 00:11:20.890
for broader collaborations.

00:11:20.890 --> 00:11:25.580
These patrons, in ways not unlike
Elizabeth Sprague Coolidge expanded

00:11:25.580 --> 00:11:29.130
the standard repertoire and
helped advance the careers

00:11:29.130 --> 00:11:33.130
of some now very well
known female composers.

00:11:33.130 --> 00:11:37.820
When Lark traveled internationally
we were generally well received.

00:11:37.820 --> 00:11:43.180
Occasionally we would be found
"charming and adorable" [laughter]

00:11:44.300 --> 00:11:46.910
or perhaps related to as
though we were a group

00:11:46.910 --> 00:11:51.090
of girls enjoying some kind
of hobby or field trip,

00:11:51.090 --> 00:11:52.800
with frequently the assumption

00:11:52.800 --> 00:11:55.610
that making a family
would inevitably take our

00:11:55.610 --> 00:11:58.110
interests elsewhere.

00:11:58.110 --> 00:12:01.690
Over the course of the 20 plus
years since I joined the group,

00:12:01.690 --> 00:12:04.070
and since my time with
Jackie du Pre,

00:12:04.070 --> 00:12:08.090
these kinds of assumptions have
diminished somewhat, and I now work

00:12:08.090 --> 00:12:11.360
with a group of students
that is mostly female.

00:12:11.360 --> 00:12:15.030
More recently in my work at cello
professor at UMass, Mount Holyoake

00:12:15.030 --> 00:12:19.280
and elsewhere, I've observed some
of the different ways in leadership

00:12:19.280 --> 00:12:21.310
and mentoring can take shape.

00:12:21.310 --> 00:12:24.330
The students in the music
department at UMass are by

00:12:24.330 --> 00:12:27.460
and large pre-professional
musicians,

00:12:27.460 --> 00:12:31.370
focusing on cello performance
and music [inaudible].

00:12:31.370 --> 00:12:33.620
When working with these
students I draw heavily

00:12:33.620 --> 00:12:38.060
on my most profound mentorships
experiences as a student,

00:12:38.060 --> 00:12:42.600 position:56%
such as my work with Jackie du Pre
or Eugene Moye, cellist in New York,

00:12:42.600 --> 00:12:44.990
or my many others teachers
and mentors.

00:12:44.990 --> 00:12:48.050
In fact, it's not uncommon in
the middle of a lesson to feel

00:12:48.050 --> 00:12:51.430
as though I'm channeling
the advice of one or another

00:12:51.430 --> 00:12:56.210
of my many teachers, when I'm
helping a student with a problem.

00:12:56.210 --> 00:13:01.110
The how to is really in
the foreground at UMass,

00:13:01.110 --> 00:13:04.290
and the pressure is on for
immediate practical results

00:13:04.290 --> 00:13:07.460
that will prepare students
for professional work.

00:13:07.460 --> 00:13:10.380
In addition to providing
musical demonstrations,

00:13:10.380 --> 00:13:14.280
I have to provide them with a
template for entering working life

00:13:14.280 --> 00:13:18.280
as a string player, whether
that involves further study

00:13:18.280 --> 00:13:23.970
or starting orchestral auditions,
or enrolling in competitions

00:13:23.970 --> 00:13:26.160
that not only can they
play all the notes,

00:13:26.160 --> 00:13:28.390
but they have internalized
the [inaudible]

00:13:28.390 --> 00:13:31.010
of the professional
musician and are prepared

00:13:31.010 --> 00:13:33.250
to collaborate successfully.

00:13:33.250 --> 00:13:34.970
This includes the understanding
that those

00:13:34.970 --> 00:13:39.890
who take a more entrepreneurial
role are more likely to succeed.

00:13:39.890 --> 00:13:41.830 position:56%
In contrast, the liberal arts agenda

00:13:41.830 --> 00:13:44.030
at Mount Holyoake College
represents --

00:13:44.030 --> 00:13:46.040
or presents me with cello students

00:13:46.040 --> 00:13:48.710
who are frequently
majoring in other fields.

00:13:48.710 --> 00:13:52.160
My role there is to give them a
deeper understanding and sense

00:13:52.160 --> 00:13:55.210
of confidence navigating
a piece of music.

00:13:55.210 --> 00:13:58.250
As a women's college with a
tradition of preparing women

00:13:58.250 --> 00:14:01.770
for leadership, the school
values classroom experience

00:14:01.770 --> 00:14:05.540
that contributes to the basic
goals of thinking independently

00:14:05.540 --> 00:14:09.810
and analytically, speaking and
writing effectively, and connecting

00:14:09.810 --> 00:14:11.990
with the broader community.

00:14:11.990 --> 00:14:16.020 position:56%
While preparing a piece of music one
draws upon many of the analytical

00:14:16.020 --> 00:14:20.050
and communication skills
required for effective leadership.

00:14:20.050 --> 00:14:22.620
In our lessons and
coaching sessions,

00:14:22.620 --> 00:14:25.290
there are surprising numbers
of parallels that can be drawn

00:14:25.290 --> 00:14:28.050
between musical performance
and clear thinking

00:14:28.050 --> 00:14:30.110
and communication in general.

00:14:30.110 --> 00:14:34.350
In true Mount Holyoake style
orchestra members rotate leadership

00:14:34.350 --> 00:14:37.800
positions, as board
members, directors of marking

00:14:37.800 --> 00:14:40.470 position:56%
and fundraising committees and more.

00:14:40.470 --> 00:14:43.740 position:56%
They are thoroughly self-sustaining.

00:14:43.740 --> 00:14:46.780
Both of these institutions
are actively engaged

00:14:46.780 --> 00:14:49.380
to advance women in
leadership roles.

00:14:49.380 --> 00:14:54.730 position:56%
For example, as recently as last
year UMass developed a program known

00:14:54.730 --> 00:14:58.780
as Priming Women for Public
Leadership, and Mount Holyoake

00:14:58.780 --> 00:15:05.440
as a vast array of programs,
including Women Leading

00:15:05.440 --> 00:15:08.690
in Public Service Summit 2015.

00:15:08.690 --> 00:15:13.970
As I prepare to join the Juilliard
faculty and my new colleagues

00:15:13.970 --> 00:15:17.590
in the Juilliard Quartet, I am
learning more about the school

00:15:17.590 --> 00:15:21.070
and the many ways it has changed
since I was a student there.

00:15:21.070 --> 00:15:24.570
To my delight, Juilliard
has made a tremendous effort

00:15:24.570 --> 00:15:26.730
to offer a broad array of courses,

00:15:26.730 --> 00:15:31.150
to the point of creating whole
departments geared toward career

00:15:31.150 --> 00:15:34.330
building, entrepreneurship,
educational outreach,

00:15:34.330 --> 00:15:37.020
mentoring and innovation.

00:15:37.020 --> 00:15:39.880
Things have changed a
lot since I was kid.

00:15:39.880 --> 00:15:43.000
Initiatives such as Julliard's
Music Advancement program,

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:45.940
the Boston Symphony
Orchestra's Project STEP,

00:15:45.940 --> 00:15:47.240
and the Sphinx Organization

00:15:47.240 --> 00:15:51.950
in Detroit have brought a much more
diverse generation of musicians

00:15:51.950 --> 00:15:55.120
into the world of music, and
that world is showing signs

00:15:55.120 --> 00:15:59.740
of being more inclusive and more
like the tapestry I grew up with.

00:15:59.740 --> 00:16:01.310
So it's very interesting to be here

00:16:01.310 --> 00:16:05.620
and hear what my two co panelists
will have to say about the state

00:16:05.620 --> 00:16:09.140
of women in music, but is
a very nice exploration.

00:16:09.140 --> 00:16:10.570
Thank you for inviting me.

00:16:10.570 --> 00:16:12.570
&gt;&gt; Annette McLean: Well,
you know, it's very resonate

00:16:12.570 --> 00:16:15.480
to hear your comments,
especially in this room

00:16:15.480 --> 00:16:18.140
with the [inaudible]
instruments there that were played

00:16:18.140 --> 00:16:21.600
for so many years by
the Budapest Quartet.

00:16:21.600 --> 00:16:23.960
And they were, as Robert
