00:16:34.950 --> 00:16:37.680
and June is a longtime -- she
came to a concert first year

00:16:37.680 --> 00:16:41.000
in 1946, so she's here tonight.

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:42.920
And for the Juilliard
we presented them --

00:16:42.920 --> 00:16:47.290 position:56%
we have presented them for 67 of the
70 years they have been in business.

00:16:47.290 --> 00:16:50.360
So the Library is a
place where stories

00:16:50.360 --> 00:16:54.400
and relationships and
families are grown.

00:16:54.400 --> 00:16:57.260
And this -- Margaret, this
applies to you very much.

00:16:57.260 --> 00:17:00.320
We -- as I say, we feel a part
of a Chamber Music America.

00:17:00.320 --> 00:17:04.030
You have been very, very hands-on
at CMA in developing a number

00:17:04.030 --> 00:17:07.980 position:56%
of new program initiatives to
encourage a diversity of expression,

00:17:07.980 --> 00:17:10.950
and we'd love to hear about that.

00:17:10.950 --> 00:17:13.360
&gt;&gt; Margaret Lioi: Well,
I'll begin by saying

00:17:13.360 --> 00:17:20.290
that I never use GPS,
I always use a map.

00:17:21.820 --> 00:17:24.390
[Applause] Now, I'm
surprised to hear applause.

00:17:24.390 --> 00:17:28.200
I thought people would probably
say, what does that have

00:17:28.200 --> 00:17:30.640
to do with women in the arts.

00:17:30.640 --> 00:17:32.160
Everything.

00:17:32.160 --> 00:17:36.980
And the reason is, I use a map
because when I'm going on a trip I

00:17:36.980 --> 00:17:42.130
like to know not just where I'm
starting from and where I'm going,

00:17:42.130 --> 00:17:46.300
but I like to know, oh, what
does the interstate cross,

00:17:46.300 --> 00:17:49.520
and maybe there are
mountains over here, or a lake

00:17:49.520 --> 00:17:54.600
or maybe I'll take a detour,
so I like the bigger picture.

00:17:54.600 --> 00:17:59.600
And I realized that I do
the same thing in my work.

00:17:59.600 --> 00:18:05.500
I don't just think of chamber
music or even the performing arts,

00:18:05.500 --> 00:18:08.070
but I look at the bigger landscape.

00:18:08.070 --> 00:18:12.030
I look at what's happening
at economically and socially

00:18:12.030 --> 00:18:15.970
and with technology and
the political landscape.

00:18:15.970 --> 00:18:22.300
And I think that we all get a
clearer picture of where we are

00:18:22.300 --> 00:18:26.790
in the larger world, where
there might be opportunities,

00:18:26.790 --> 00:18:30.790
where there might be
gaps that we can fill in.

00:18:30.790 --> 00:18:34.470
So thinking of this conversation

00:18:34.470 --> 00:18:38.170
in the larger context
I thought I would start

00:18:38.170 --> 00:18:41.800
out where I often start out,
which is the Census Bureau.

00:18:41.800 --> 00:18:46.980
I love reading Census Bureau
statistics [laughter].

00:18:46.980 --> 00:18:52.040
I know it sounds a little boring,
but really you can find out so much

00:18:52.040 --> 00:18:56.610
about where you are and
where you might want to go.

00:18:56.610 --> 00:19:01.040
So according to the Census
Bureau women's presence

00:19:01.040 --> 00:19:06.770
in the labor force has increased
dramatically, from about 30 million

00:19:06.770 --> 00:19:12.450
in 1970 to 73 million in 2010.

00:19:12.450 --> 00:19:17.020
Now to put that into
context, in 1970 there were

00:19:17.020 --> 00:19:20.020
about 80 million workers total,

00:19:20.020 --> 00:19:25.500
so of those total workers,
about 38% were women.

00:19:25.500 --> 00:19:32.630
And in 2010 there were 154
million workers, so the percentage

00:19:32.630 --> 00:19:37.000
of women had risen to about 47%.

00:19:37.000 --> 00:19:40.630
But the types of jobs
that most women held

00:19:40.630 --> 00:19:48.020
in 1970 were dental assistants,
teachers, secretaries and nurses.

00:19:48.020 --> 00:19:52.810
And in fact, I graduated from
high school right around that time

00:19:52.810 --> 00:19:57.540
and I was one of three women
out of -- we had a class --

00:19:57.540 --> 00:20:01.560
I went to a women's high school,
we had a class of about 200.

00:20:01.560 --> 00:20:06.320
I was one of three that was
pursuing a career in the arts,

00:20:06.320 --> 00:20:08.910
all the other classmates were going

00:20:08.910 --> 00:20:12.010
to nursing school or
becoming teachers.

00:20:12.010 --> 00:20:16.480
And that was actually confirmed
at my last high school reunion,

00:20:16.480 --> 00:20:19.290
when we found that in fact most

00:20:19.290 --> 00:20:24.690
of the class had had careers
in teaching and nursing.

00:20:24.690 --> 00:20:29.160
The career guidance available
at that time for women wanting

00:20:29.160 --> 00:20:33.450
to pursue a performing
career didn't exist.

00:20:33.450 --> 00:20:36.540
I studied piano with the
Eastman School of Music

00:20:36.540 --> 00:20:41.920
in the Preparatory Division, and
my teacher wanted me to continue

00:20:41.920 --> 00:20:44.760
in the college division of Eastman,

00:20:44.760 --> 00:20:48.880
but I wanted to expand
my world view.

00:20:48.880 --> 00:20:54.380
Now expand my worldview is a
euphemism for I wanted to get

00:20:54.380 --> 00:20:57.180
out of Rochester, New
York [laughter],

00:20:58.710 --> 00:21:04.270
even though Eastman is a wonderful
school, but I just felt there had

00:21:04.270 --> 00:21:09.630 position:56%
to be a place where the sun came out
more than in Rochester, New York.

00:21:09.630 --> 00:21:15.380
Now I had absolutely no
idea what I was doing.

00:21:15.380 --> 00:21:19.080
There were some well known
women pianists at the time,

00:21:19.080 --> 00:21:22.710
but I didn't particularly
want to be a performer,

00:21:22.710 --> 00:21:27.510
I just knew that I loved
music, I loved the piano,

00:21:27.510 --> 00:21:32.600
and I wanted in some way to have
a career in the performing arts.

00:21:32.600 --> 00:21:37.300
So the way I could see that
at that time was to continue

00:21:37.300 --> 00:21:40.990
with the instrument that
I had been studying.

00:21:40.990 --> 00:21:45.220
So we'll fast forward through four
years of college and two years

00:21:45.220 --> 00:21:50.340
of graduate school, and after
six years I had much improved

00:21:50.340 --> 00:21:55.200
as a musician and had as
few prospects for employment

00:21:55.200 --> 00:21:58.800
as I had had six years before.

00:21:58.800 --> 00:22:02.550
And, again, there were few
women professors of piano

00:22:02.550 --> 00:22:04.190
at New England Conservatory.

00:22:04.190 --> 00:22:10.500 position:56%
They were not young women, and I
really could not identify with them.

00:22:10.500 --> 00:22:12.820
My old teacher was a man,

00:22:12.820 --> 00:22:17.340
a wonderful man named Jacob
Maxim, excellent teacher.

00:22:17.340 --> 00:22:18.960
I loved him.

00:22:18.960 --> 00:22:24.390
But he was not a mentor,
he was very reclusive.

00:22:24.390 --> 00:22:29.540
As a matter of fact, he himself had
stopped performing because he had

00:22:29.540 --> 00:22:33.190
such anxiety before
he got onto the stage.

00:22:33.190 --> 00:22:35.120
And so I thought, I'm not sure

00:22:35.120 --> 00:22:39.450
that that's really the person
I want for a mentor [laughter].

00:22:39.450 --> 00:22:41.300
But we remained close,

00:22:41.300 --> 00:22:45.390
he just passed away recently,
he was a wonderful man.

00:22:45.390 --> 00:22:49.370
But after I graduated I
became a freelance musician,

00:22:49.370 --> 00:22:51.700
primarily for vocalists.

00:22:51.700 --> 00:22:55.750
And this actually turned into
a career as an accompanist,

00:22:55.750 --> 00:22:59.700
which is now of course
called collaborative piano.

00:22:59.700 --> 00:23:03.860
And I often say, if it had
truly been collaborative

00:23:03.860 --> 00:23:07.510
when I was doing it I would have
remained in that profession.

00:23:07.510 --> 00:23:10.090
[ Laughter ]

00:23:10.090 --> 00:23:13.890
I played with some
wonderful musicians, I toured,

00:23:13.890 --> 00:23:18.180
I played for opera rehearsals and
dance classes and music theater,

00:23:18.180 --> 00:23:20.440
you name it and I played for it.

00:23:20.440 --> 00:23:25.750
Freelancers live in fear of
never getting another job,

00:23:25.750 --> 00:23:30.610
so you take any job at any
time that comes your way,

00:23:30.610 --> 00:23:34.620
and that becomes its own
problem which is another panel,

00:23:34.620 --> 00:23:37.490
which we'll schedule
some time [laughter].

00:23:37.490 --> 00:23:40.980
So this went on until I turned 30,

00:23:40.980 --> 00:23:48.690 position:56%
and I had this really lightning bolt
realization that I had no savings,

00:23:48.690 --> 00:23:52.960
no stability, I was
working seven days a week,

00:23:52.960 --> 00:23:55.970
and I had lost a clear direction.

00:23:55.970 --> 00:23:59.280
My direction became maintenance.

00:23:59.280 --> 00:24:05.000
Did I have enough money for
rent, food, and gas for my car.

00:24:05.000 --> 00:24:09.840
It was a very short-term plan,
very short-term existence.

00:24:09.840 --> 00:24:12.620
So at that time I met a woman

00:24:12.620 --> 00:24:16.860
who was getting an MBA
in Arts Administration.

00:24:16.860 --> 00:24:21.210
I had no idea that
such a thing existed.

00:24:21.210 --> 00:24:26.510
There was actually a job
called an Arts Administrator.

00:24:26.510 --> 00:24:31.920
And it does seem ridiculous to
me now, but at that time I was

00:24:31.920 --> 00:24:35.610
so focused on playing that
it never occurred to me

00:24:35.610 --> 00:24:38.350
that someone was actually in charge

00:24:38.350 --> 00:24:42.160
of the organizations
that were hiring me.

00:24:42.160 --> 00:24:47.250
So let's -- we'll fast forward
again for another couple of years.

00:24:47.250 --> 00:24:49.980 position:56%
I did get my MBA and I began to work

00:24:49.980 --> 00:24:54.230
for arts organizations
on the business side.

00:24:54.230 --> 00:24:57.940
So now that I'm running
a national organization,

00:24:57.940 --> 00:25:03.340
I'd like to share a few things
that I have observed in my career.

00:25:03.340 --> 00:25:08.870
They're not necessarily related,
but they all sort of fit the idea

00:25:08.870 --> 00:25:12.290
that we're talking about tonight.

00:25:12.290 --> 00:25:15.400
I've never had a female boss.

00:25:15.400 --> 00:25:20.060
Every organization I've worked
for has been led by men.

00:25:20.060 --> 00:25:25.330
They're wonderful, smart,
talented, creative and charismatic,

00:25:25.330 --> 00:25:33.770
but I think it's interesting that
since I had come up in my career,

00:25:33.770 --> 00:25:38.120
so many more organizations
are run by women.

00:25:38.120 --> 00:25:41.110
And I'll get to that
in just a moment.

00:25:41.110 --> 00:25:45.080
According to the National
Partnership for Women and Families,

00:25:45.080 --> 00:25:52.130
on average, women earn 77 cents
for every dollar earned by men.

00:25:52.130 --> 00:25:56.910
And I did experience this firsthand
when I moved to New York to work

00:25:56.910 --> 00:25:58.810
for the Charitable Trust.

00:25:58.810 --> 00:26:01.030 position:56%
My predecessor had been a gentleman,

00:26:01.030 --> 00:26:05.130
and since I was the
trust's chief administrator,

00:26:05.130 --> 00:26:08.010
I had payroll responsibilities.

00:26:08.010 --> 00:26:14.260
So in reviewing the payroll records
it came to [laughter] my attention

00:26:14.260 --> 00:26:22.920
that I was being paid exactly
50% less than he had been paid.

00:26:22.920 --> 00:26:26.060
That was quite a shock.

00:26:26.060 --> 00:26:31.560
There are still very few
mentorship programs for women

00:26:31.560 --> 00:26:36.550
who are interested in pursuing
arts administration career paths.

00:26:36.550 --> 00:26:39.370
There are many women who
are members of ensembles

00:26:39.370 --> 00:26:44.250
and notably some ensembles are
composed entirely of women.

00:26:44.250 --> 00:26:49.950
But there are still relatively
few women in major orchestras.

00:26:49.950 --> 00:26:51.940
The paths from performing

00:26:51.940 --> 00:26:55.070
to administration are
very serendipitous.

00:26:55.070 --> 00:26:59.400
There are few official structures
where performers can know

00:26:59.400 --> 00:27:05.890
about the existence of arts jobs
and arts administration programs.

00:27:05.890 --> 00:27:10.140
The wage discrepancy issue that I
mentioned earlier has been talked

00:27:10.140 --> 00:27:15.540
about for years, but another
aspect of this conversation

00:27:15.540 --> 00:27:20.330
that women continue to face
is the work/life balance.

00:27:20.330 --> 00:27:23.540
Our cultural understanding
of mothers

00:27:23.540 --> 00:27:27.890
and fathers roles really
must be further examined,

00:27:27.890 --> 00:27:34.700 position:56%
and our administrative work places
need to become more family friendly.

00:27:34.700 --> 00:27:37.470
Young women who look to
the arts for careers have

00:27:37.470 --> 00:27:42.990
so many high profile role models
now that didn't exist years ago.

00:27:42.990 --> 00:27:47.630
In addition to my co panelists
who have very high profile

00:27:47.630 --> 00:27:52.220
and prominent jobs in the
arts, there's Deborah Borda

00:27:52.220 --> 00:27:55.870
who is president and CEO of
the Los Angeles Philharmonic,

00:27:55.870 --> 00:27:59.070
and the Fellow New England
Conservatory [inaudible] I'm happy

00:27:59.070 --> 00:28:00.370
to say.

00:28:00.370 --> 00:28:04.900
There's your own Deborah Rutter who
is president of the Kennedy Center,

00:28:04.900 --> 00:28:08.020
and before that of
the Chicago Symphony.

00:28:08.020 --> 00:28:12.870
And we just saw Marin Alsop, Music
Director of the Baltimore Symphony.

00:28:12.870 --> 00:28:17.700
So these women who are prominent
in the arts, in administration,

00:28:17.700 --> 00:28:23.600
and in performing, and they
can become now role models

00:28:23.600 --> 00:28:25.310
for the younger generation.

00:28:25.310 --> 00:28:29.640
They have become role
models for younger women.

00:28:29.640 --> 00:28:34.080
So I have a vision for the field
of arts of administration that I'd

00:28:34.080 --> 00:28:39.180
like to share with
you for the year 2025.

00:28:39.180 --> 00:28:42.770
We'll reconvene then maybe,
Anne, and we'll have this panel

00:28:42.770 --> 00:28:45.970
and see if we've gotten there.

00:28:45.970 --> 00:28:50.730
Learning the principles of arts
administration will be required

00:28:50.730 --> 00:28:54.070
for anyone studying
the performing arts.

00:28:54.070 --> 00:28:57.140
This will be the norm
and not the exception.

00:28:57.140 --> 00:29:00.730
For those seeking arts
administration careers,

00:29:00.730 --> 00:29:05.140
paid internships will
part of their curriculum.

00:29:05.140 --> 00:29:09.620
Salaries in arts administration
positions will not be lower

00:29:09.620 --> 00:29:12.900
than their counterparts
in the for profit arena.

00:29:12.900 --> 00:29:18.490
And artists and arts administrators
will be welcomed additions

00:29:18.490 --> 00:29:22.680
to the boards of civic
organizations and corporations

00:29:22.680 --> 00:29:26.020
because of the creativity
and innovative thinking

00:29:26.020 --> 00:29:28.190
that they bring to the table.

00:29:28.190 --> 00:29:33.870
And there will be parody among men
and women in wages, family care,

00:29:33.870 --> 00:29:37.370
and job opportunities
throughout the field.

00:29:37.370 --> 00:29:40.180
I think we can do it,
and I look forward

00:29:40.180 --> 00:29:42.320
to being a part of that world.

00:29:42.320 --> 00:29:44.120
Thank you.

00:29:44.120 --> 00:29:50.110
[ Applause ]

00:29:50.110 --> 00:29:51.410
&gt;&gt; Annette McLean: Wonderful.

00:29:51.410 --> 00:29:54.380
And Chairman Chu, you have
the very broadest overview

00:29:54.380 --> 00:29:57.310
of all aspects of music
in our nation.

00:29:57.310 --> 00:30:00.660
&gt;&gt; Jane Chu: Well, I -- now
I'm in a position where I focus

00:30:00.660 --> 00:30:05.190
on all the arts, all the
genders, and appreciate them all.

00:30:05.190 --> 00:30:09.720
But I come today with a perspective
of my own love for music,

00:30:09.720 --> 00:30:11.210
and my own musical training

00:30:11.210 --> 00:30:16.130
and how it has informed
my own leadership style.

00:30:16.130 --> 00:30:18.910
I don't think that there's
ever been a better time

00:30:18.910 --> 00:30:22.660
to appreciate what the arts can
provide in terms of leadership.

00:30:22.660 --> 00:30:26.190
Because we live in this world that
is filled with constant change,

00:30:26.190 --> 00:30:29.000
and there's new information
flying toward us

00:30:29.000 --> 00:30:31.760
from multiple directions
simultaneously

00:30:31.760 --> 00:30:35.800
and everybody has an opinion and
everybody wants the opinion heard.

00:30:35.800 --> 00:30:39.620
And so we need creative
leaders who will sort through

00:30:39.620 --> 00:30:41.390
and bring together
those [inaudible] pieces

00:30:41.390 --> 00:30:44.660
and who will find new
solutions to be able

00:30:44.660 --> 00:30:46.840
to bridge those opposing
perspectives.

00:30:46.840 --> 00:30:51.380
And for me, and possible for
you, and certainly my panelists,

00:30:51.380 --> 00:30:57.070 position:56%
the arts are a key piece in building
new paths toward this common ground.

00:30:57.070 --> 00:30:59.600
So I was born into
multiple cultures,

00:30:59.600 --> 00:31:02.000
often with seemingly
opposing perspectives,

00:31:02.000 --> 00:31:04.910
and if I had not been involved
in the arts I'm not sure

00:31:04.910 --> 00:31:08.170
that I would have been able to
make as much sense of my own life.

00:31:08.170 --> 00:31:12.060
My parents met in the United
States, but both came from China,

00:31:12.060 --> 00:31:15.880
during a time when their home
country was in a lot of turmoil.

00:31:15.880 --> 00:31:21.730
They came to America in the
1940s, or 1948 and 1949,

00:31:21.730 --> 00:31:24.080
and they never saw
their families again.

00:31:24.080 --> 00:31:27.780
I on the other hand was born in
Oklahoma and I grew up in Arkansas,

