00:45:51.820 --> 00:45:56.140
and then that was sort of
the low rung for pianists.

00:45:56.140 --> 00:46:01.740
And then you would maybe play for
education programs in schools.

00:46:01.740 --> 00:46:04.850
Then you might get
a gig with a singer

00:46:04.850 --> 00:46:08.110
and you could have a
few weeks of the tour.

00:46:08.110 --> 00:46:11.800
And I'm sure it was the
same for string players.

00:46:11.800 --> 00:46:20.020 position:56%
You would start doing things to get
credentials, but your goal was to go

00:46:20.020 --> 00:46:25.650
up the ladder, and eventually
play, you know, at Carnegie Hall

00:46:25.650 --> 00:46:27.730
or at the Kennedy Center.

00:46:27.730 --> 00:46:35.730
And now success is not looked
at so much as a vertical line,

00:46:35.730 --> 00:46:39.520
but much more as a
horizontal continuum.

00:46:39.520 --> 00:46:45.200
So that people who play
engagements in schools,

00:46:45.200 --> 00:46:48.740
education is so important,
and reaching young people is

00:46:48.740 --> 00:46:53.080
so important, and they'll
do that maybe on a Thursday,

00:46:53.080 --> 00:46:55.970
and then on Friday they're
playing in the concert hall.

00:46:55.970 --> 00:46:59.300
And then on Saturday maybe
they decide they're playing

00:46:59.300 --> 00:47:01.910
in a coffee shop, just
to reach people

00:47:01.910 --> 00:47:04.330
that maybe didn't come
to the concert hall.

00:47:04.330 --> 00:47:08.500
So musicians and administrators

00:47:08.500 --> 00:47:14.270 position:56%
as well I think are defining success
not as starting at the bottom

00:47:14.270 --> 00:47:19.500
and going to the top, but what
makes you happy every day,

00:47:19.500 --> 00:47:22.560
what makes you fulfilled every day.

00:47:22.560 --> 00:47:24.260 position:56%
And I think that's a big difference.

00:47:24.260 --> 00:47:33.230
I think that technology and
expressing yourself publically

00:47:33.230 --> 00:47:37.520
in a different kind
of way from certainly

00:47:37.520 --> 00:47:41.800
when I was a younger person,
that was not acceptable.

00:47:41.800 --> 00:47:44.600
There were -- there were only
a few people who were allowed

00:47:44.600 --> 00:47:48.440
to have opinions and those people
were called critics [laughter].

00:47:48.440 --> 00:47:51.100
And it isn't that way anymore.

00:47:51.100 --> 00:47:56.330
So I think that success has
redefined itself really.

00:47:56.330 --> 00:47:57.630
&gt;&gt; Annette McLean: Excellent.

00:47:57.630 --> 00:47:58.930
Excellent.

00:47:58.930 --> 00:48:00.230
You talked the other day

00:48:00.230 --> 00:48:03.610
about having said something there
many kinds of artistic excellences

00:48:03.610 --> 00:48:07.110
in many paths, and I --
that -- I remembered that.

00:48:07.110 --> 00:48:11.350
This has been very interesting,
and we appreciate your thoughts

00:48:11.350 --> 00:48:13.350
on the subject of leadership.

00:48:13.350 --> 00:48:15.330
And I know that time is
running out so I want

00:48:15.330 --> 00:48:16.780
to give the audience a chance

00:48:16.780 --> 00:48:18.940
to ask some questions,
if you would like to.

00:48:18.940 --> 00:48:21.770
We can open it up now
for just a few moment.

00:48:21.770 --> 00:48:23.070
And we'll have the
microphones coming

00:48:23.070 --> 00:48:26.570 position:56%
around just here to facilitate this.

00:48:26.570 --> 00:48:27.870
Okay.

00:48:27.870 --> 00:48:29.680
&gt;&gt; I just wanted to thank --

00:48:29.680 --> 00:48:35.110
everyone of your statements has
been just so incredibly meaningful.

00:48:35.110 --> 00:48:36.710
I wanted to thank you all.

00:48:36.710 --> 00:48:38.010
&gt;&gt; Margaret Lioi: Thank you.

00:48:38.010 --> 00:48:40.820
&gt;&gt; And as I was listening to
each one of you, for example,

00:48:40.820 --> 00:48:45.340
I went through school,
high school, college

00:48:45.340 --> 00:48:48.700
and graduate school never
having a single women professor

00:48:48.700 --> 00:48:52.550
in chemistry, in the
sciences, at all.

00:48:52.550 --> 00:48:56.580
And so the parallels
between music and science

00:48:56.580 --> 00:49:00.890
in our career times is identical.

00:49:00.890 --> 00:49:06.330
And I applaud the Creativity
Connects, because I have to say

00:49:06.330 --> 00:49:12.350
that most of the women scientists
I know also play an instrument,

00:49:12.350 --> 00:49:13.730
and that's almost, you know,

00:49:13.730 --> 00:49:18.550
an absolutely necessary
therapeutic counterbalance

00:49:18.550 --> 00:49:22.560
to that solitary scientific
endeavor.

00:49:22.560 --> 00:49:27.520
And so I wanted to ask, though,
for example, the media lab at MIT,

00:49:27.520 --> 00:49:29.520
which I happen to know
very well, has --

00:49:29.520 --> 00:49:31.910
you know, the media is [inaudible].

00:49:31.910 --> 00:49:37.520
And so the arts and the sciences
have intertwined over the years,

00:49:37.520 --> 00:49:39.950 position:56%
not necessarily with women involved.

00:49:39.950 --> 00:49:45.500
But I guess I'm interested
in your perspective

00:49:45.500 --> 00:49:49.370
on the historical connection
and how that feeds into some

00:49:49.370 --> 00:49:58.950
of the connectivities of -- and
perhaps if you have some experience

00:49:58.950 --> 00:50:03.600
through your own musical education,
you mentioned at Mount Holyoake.

00:50:03.600 --> 00:50:07.270
You're obviously dealing with
cellists who are majoring

00:50:07.270 --> 00:50:12.010
in non-music, if you have
any comments on that as well.

00:50:12.010 --> 00:50:13.310
&gt;&gt; Astrid Schween: Yeah, sure.

00:50:13.310 --> 00:50:16.720
Well, that's one of the reasons I
enjoy my position at Mount Holyoake

00:50:16.720 --> 00:50:19.140 position:56%
so much -- it's just a little short.

00:50:19.140 --> 00:50:20.510
There we go.

00:50:20.510 --> 00:50:24.690
I do, as I said, work with so many
young women who are, you know,

00:50:24.690 --> 00:50:31.290 position:56%
likely future chairman's of major --
chairpersons of major corporations

00:50:31.290 --> 00:50:34.330
or possibly even future presidents.

00:50:34.330 --> 00:50:39.040
They're so bright and so
ambitious, and so creative.

00:50:39.040 --> 00:50:43.150
And when they take the time to
come for a weekly cello lesson

00:50:43.150 --> 00:50:46.200
or a chamber music session, I find
it's a great opportunity for us

00:50:46.200 --> 00:50:50.200
to connect on this, especially
in the level of communication.

00:50:50.200 --> 00:50:54.420
And how does one find
a voice and amplify

00:50:54.420 --> 00:50:57.120
that through the texture
of the group.

00:50:57.120 --> 00:51:01.040
Specifically you talked about
media and how that interacts

00:51:01.040 --> 00:51:02.650
with -- intersects with music.

00:51:02.650 --> 00:51:05.070
I think -- you know, I was
listing several classes

00:51:05.070 --> 00:51:07.670
that Juilliard has offered,
and I have to say as somebody

00:51:07.670 --> 00:51:10.490
who is stepping in, I
grew up at that school,

00:51:10.490 --> 00:51:15.150 position:56%
I was there from age seven to 20, so
I do feel like there's a little bit

00:51:15.150 --> 00:51:18.300
of my blood on the walls
everywhere [laughter].

00:51:18.300 --> 00:51:21.280
And I'm just so impressed now
coming back as a professor

00:51:21.280 --> 00:51:25.790
to see the innovations that have
been made by President Polisi

00:51:25.790 --> 00:51:28.200
and that he's addressing
this very issue.

00:51:28.200 --> 00:51:32.670
That it's not enough to be
creative within your own Scarlatti

00:51:32.670 --> 00:51:35.130
or [inaudible], but you
have to create a world

00:51:35.130 --> 00:51:36.540
in which you can share this music.

00:51:36.540 --> 00:51:41.390
And I think it's no accident that
classical music became so kind

00:51:41.390 --> 00:51:43.050
of single minded for a while,

00:51:43.050 --> 00:51:47.120
and was not successful
at being all inclusive.

00:51:47.120 --> 00:51:50.470
So in a way, to have
our young people now

00:51:50.470 --> 00:51:52.550
who are students use the media.

00:51:52.550 --> 00:51:56.390
They're using social media, they're
doing all sorts of things to get --

00:51:56.390 --> 00:52:00.590
to connect young people and
introduce them to classical music.

00:52:00.590 --> 00:52:02.350
I think it's fantastic.

00:52:02.350 --> 00:52:04.080
Exposure is everything.

00:52:04.080 --> 00:52:06.050
It's the reason I play the cello,

00:52:06.050 --> 00:52:11.350
and I imagine my colleagues here
had some similar experiences.

00:52:13.490 --> 00:52:18.290
&gt;&gt; Hi. Very much appreciate
all that you all are doing.

00:52:18.290 --> 00:52:21.670
Thank you very much for all
your dedication and commitment,

00:52:21.670 --> 00:52:25.580
because I know it must have been
mammoth over all these years.

00:52:25.580 --> 00:52:29.490
And I would just like to give a
little shout out to the composers.

00:52:29.490 --> 00:52:30.790
&gt;&gt; Jane Chu: Yeah.

00:52:30.790 --> 00:52:37.070
&gt;&gt; It seems like still that's a
section that is missing somehow.

00:52:37.070 --> 00:52:41.880
I think of the commissions done
here by the Library of Congress,

00:52:41.880 --> 00:52:46.040
and I wonder how many
have been won by women.

00:52:46.040 --> 00:52:51.610
When they were talking about
their panel several months ago,

00:52:51.610 --> 00:52:57.300
and picking people, I said,
do you do an anonymous

00:52:57.300 --> 00:52:59.420
or do you do it some other way.

00:52:59.420 --> 00:53:02.500
And they said, "No, we
know who we're seating."

00:53:02.500 --> 00:53:08.590
And I just wonder if some blind
competitions might be better

00:53:08.590 --> 00:53:15.790 position:56%
to give women a chance that perhaps
unconsciously the men may not be as,

00:53:15.790 --> 00:53:19.020
you know, accepting of.

00:53:19.020 --> 00:53:25.540
But also in general, I can't think
of a single woman composer or note,

00:53:25.540 --> 00:53:27.880
except in the popular field.

00:53:27.880 --> 00:53:35.200
Meredith Monk, Carol --
what's her name, Carol King.

00:53:35.200 --> 00:53:37.960
What's that?

00:53:37.960 --> 00:53:42.340
Carol Sager [assumed
spelling], just in popular field.

00:53:42.340 --> 00:53:45.580
I can't think -- I can't
think of a lot of --

00:53:45.580 --> 00:53:46.880
&gt;&gt; Annette McLean: I think

00:53:46.880 --> 00:53:48.180
of Jennifer Higdon [assumed
spelling] and [inaudible].

00:53:48.180 --> 00:53:49.480
We're so pleased to say that --

00:53:49.480 --> 00:53:53.390
&gt;&gt; Okay. Except [inaudible]
back in the 16th Century.

00:53:53.390 --> 00:53:58.650
So I'm just hoping that all of you
all who are on panels are watching

00:53:58.650 --> 00:54:01.280
out for the women who are
trying to get into that.

00:54:01.280 --> 00:54:02.580
&gt;&gt; Annette McLean: I know

00:54:02.580 --> 00:54:04.510
that Chamber Music America is
very, very much aware of this.

00:54:04.510 --> 00:54:06.390
And, Margaret, we've
talked about this

00:54:06.390 --> 00:54:10.420
about how gender blind listening
is important, and how you encourage

00:54:10.420 --> 00:54:12.960
and seek out submissions for women.

00:54:12.960 --> 00:54:15.710
And I can respond briefly on
behalf of the Library saying

00:54:15.710 --> 00:54:18.060
that we are very excited
that we do have a number

00:54:18.060 --> 00:54:21.010 position:56%
of important substantive commissions

00:54:21.010 --> 00:54:23.200
by female composers
in the last few years.

00:54:23.200 --> 00:54:25.000
And we have a couple
more coming up this year.

00:54:25.000 --> 00:54:26.850
If you look at our
brochure we are going

00:54:26.850 --> 00:54:30.210
to have Gabriella Alana
Fronk [assumed spelling],

00:54:30.210 --> 00:54:33.570
a new [inaudible] from
her [inaudible] Society.

00:54:33.570 --> 00:54:35.410 position:56%
But talk a little bit about -- yeah.

00:54:35.410 --> 00:54:37.210
This is --

00:54:37.210 --> 00:54:42.070
[ Inaudible Speaker ]

00:54:42.070 --> 00:54:43.890
Or we can swap microphones
for a second.

00:54:43.890 --> 00:54:45.910
&gt;&gt; Jane Chu: There you go.

00:54:45.910 --> 00:54:47.730
Go ahead.

00:54:47.730 --> 00:54:49.270
&gt;&gt; Margaret Lioi: Thank you.

00:54:49.270 --> 00:54:54.650
Yes, actually Caroline Shaw just
won the Pulitzer Prize last year

00:54:54.650 --> 00:54:55.950
for music.

00:54:55.950 --> 00:54:57.250
I think it was last year.

00:54:57.250 --> 00:55:02.660
And we have many, many --
actually Chamber Music America has

00:55:02.660 --> 00:55:05.290
commissioned many women composers.

00:55:05.290 --> 00:55:11.110
But you are absolutely right, they
are not as prominently programmed

00:55:11.110 --> 00:55:15.140
as male composers on
chamber music programs.

00:55:15.140 --> 00:55:18.330
I can only speak for chamber music.

00:55:18.330 --> 00:55:22.980
But we do an awful lot of outreach.

00:55:22.980 --> 00:55:29.860 position:56%
When we are having our commissioning
program we contact the women

00:55:29.860 --> 00:55:35.430
who have received commissions by
us, and ask them to, you know,

00:55:35.430 --> 00:55:39.660
spread the word so that
more women will apply.

00:55:39.660 --> 00:55:43.360
We've also -- we have a conference
every years, and we have had many,

00:55:43.360 --> 00:55:48.250
many sessions on programming
compositions by women.

00:55:48.250 --> 00:55:54.410
It's a an issue in the
classical musical field,

00:55:54.410 --> 00:55:57.630
it is even a bigger
issue in the jazz field.

00:55:57.630 --> 00:56:01.270
There are so few women
jazz musicians

00:56:01.270 --> 00:56:08.090 position:56%
and women jazz band leaders, and I
think this is just part of the field

00:56:08.090 --> 00:56:11.930
that has to be brought
up to the same level

00:56:11.930 --> 00:56:14.330
as the performing parts
of the field.

00:56:14.330 --> 00:56:18.480
And to do it I think we
have to be very intentional.

00:56:18.480 --> 00:56:22.530
There have to be some very
intentional steps taken

00:56:22.530 --> 00:56:27.230 position:56%
so that women have the opportunities
to compose and to be programmed.

00:56:27.230 --> 00:56:29.700
So thank you for bringing that up.

00:56:29.700 --> 00:56:31.720
&gt;&gt; Annette McLean: I
