00:56:31.720 --> 00:56:34.500
that you might find interesting,
unfortunately we're --

00:56:34.500 --> 00:56:36.760
I think we're almost out of time.

00:56:36.760 --> 00:56:40.570
But the Guardian actually has a
lot of coverage of these kinds

00:56:40.570 --> 00:56:42.870
of issues, the British newspaper.

00:56:42.870 --> 00:56:46.930
And there was an article very
recently how the male domination

00:56:46.930 --> 00:56:49.150
of classical music
may finally be coming

00:56:49.150 --> 00:56:51.430
to an end, which is interesting.

00:56:51.430 --> 00:56:53.640
But the article [inaudible] Jessica
Ducheon [assumed spelling] is the

00:56:53.640 --> 00:56:54.940
women who wrote the article.

00:56:54.940 --> 00:56:58.700
But what resonated in the back of
my mind about this was she talks

00:56:58.700 --> 00:57:02.470
about the BBC recently,
Radio 3, did long series

00:57:02.470 --> 00:57:05.540
of radio programs about
women composers.

00:57:05.540 --> 00:57:09.700
And recently there was
a British music exam

00:57:09.700 --> 00:57:12.030
on which almost no
composers were women,

00:57:12.030 --> 00:57:15.090
or maybe only one was on the exam.

00:57:15.090 --> 00:57:16.870
So this is a very timely issue.

00:57:16.870 --> 00:57:19.170
But the great news is
that there is a lot

00:57:19.170 --> 00:57:23.310
of very exciting things happening
and going on in this area.

00:57:23.310 --> 00:57:27.370
So maybe just one more question,
then we need to go to the concert.

00:57:28.610 --> 00:57:31.960
&gt;&gt; Good evening everyone, I'm
Kristy Wagner [assumed spelling],

00:57:31.960 --> 00:57:35.250
Starlee Wagner is my pen name,
